It takes a village to put America’s Newsroom on television five days a week, but it took one person to make it a family.
 
Alan Komissaroff saw ANR’s success from the beginning. Without his incredible vision and news judgement at the helm as Executive Producer, the show would not have become the success it is today. 
 
You rarely hear about what goes on behind the scenes during these shows but let us tell you. Alan was an amazing father and lit up whenever asked about his two children. He was an incredible boss and if you had the privilege of working for him you know he always made sure you had a seat at the table. His sense of humor made the 4 am wake up calls worth it and carried you through the hard days of news.
 
We hope whoever is reading this has an Alan in their life. If you are so lucky, please reach out and tell them how much they mean to you.

To donate to Alan’s family please visit https://www.gofundme.com/f/r873bv-the-komissaroff-family

URGENT SITUATION IN HAITI: THE FATE OF ABDUCTED AMERICAN NURSE & HER CHILD REMAINS UNCERTAIN. 

An American nurse and her daughter were abducted by armed men while serving in a Christian community ministry in Haiti on Thursday. The situation in Port-au-Prince has escalated, prompting the US State Department to order non-emergency government personnel and family members to leave the country due to kidnapping, crime, civil unrest, and poor healthcare infrastructure.

There have already been over 1,000 kidnappings in Haiti from January to June this year. According to the World Bank, Haiti is the poorest country in the Western Hemisphere, with 60% of its population living below the poverty line.

Former NFL player and founder of the Brewer Foundation, Jack Brewer, joins us today to share his firsthand experience with charity and volunteer work in Haiti: "Literally gangs running the country, and when you look at the numbers, those numbers are low, they're actually much higher... this is real... These gangs are funded by current politicians, whether they're the senators or the parliament members, that's where they're getting these weapons..."

To learn more & donate, visit: https://thejackbrewerfoundation.org/

22 YEARS LATER: REMEMBERING 9/11.
We will #NeverForget. 

Today, we pause to reflect and pay tribute to the many lives lost during the tragic events of September 11, 2001.

On the evening of Sept. 11, 2001, President George W. Bush addressed the nation from the Oval Office in a speech that explained a key doctrine of his administration’s future foreign policy: "We will make no distinction between the terrorists who committed these acts and those who harbor them," President Bush said on that date.

Three days after the attacks, on Sept. 14, 2001, President Bush visited Ground Zero, the smoking pile of debris of what remained of the World Trade Center and the thousands who had perished there.

Standing atop a fire truck, President Bush used a bullhorn to address rescue workers who were toiling to find survivors.

When one of the workers said that he could not hear what the president was saying, President Bush exclaimed, "I can hear you. The rest of the world hears you. And the people who knocked these buildings down will hear from all of us soon."
